		<div id="content"><div style="margin: 10px; text-align: left;"></div>
<div style="padding: 3px; margin-right: 3px;">
<div class="item">
  <div class="itemHead"><span class="itemTitle"><a href="http://www.longliveafrica.com/modules/news/index.php?storytopic=1"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-2">Business</kw></a><kw class="krdwrd-tag-2">&nbsp;:&nbsp;SPIN VS SUBSTANCE IN MARKETING AFRICA</kw></span></div>
  <div class="itemInfo">
    <span class="itemPoster"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">Posted by </kw><a href="http://www.longliveafrica.com/userinfo.php?uid=1"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">admin</kw></a></span> <span class="itemPostDate"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">on 2005/6/8 7:15:10</kw></span><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1"> (</kw><span class="itemStats"><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">2095 reads</kw></span><kw class="krdwrd-tag-1">)
  </kw></div>
  <div class="itemBody">
    
    <p class="itemText"><strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">Africa seems to make headlines only when there are pictures of starving children, war, or people with HIV-AIDS.</kw><br><br><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">The U.K. based </kw><strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">Development Studies Association</kw></strong><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3"> took time out last month to ask why, and what impacts these negative images are having on Africa’s investment climate.</kw></strong><br><br><br></p><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">Convenor of the Association’s Media Development Group, Ms Frances Hill, said the meeting “generated heated debate among the wide range of delegates who participated.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“The whole point of the meeting - the first for our Media Development Group – was to see if a co-ordinated marketing plan for Africa could help promote positive images and hence investment into African economies.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">&nbsp;“We heard from a number of people who’ve been working in the international development field for a long, long time,” said Ms Hill.&nbsp; “Many see marketing as a quick fix option, as spin – they don’t want to sully their good work with that sort of thing.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“On the other hand, we had several delegates from Africa, the director of the African Diaspora Association among them, who saw the continent’s negative image as a real problem.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“I view marketing not as a single solution,” said Ms Hill, “but as part of the toolbox that development professionals can use to improve the prospects of people in disadvantaged areas.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“There is a view, represented at the meeting, that non government organisations working to obtain funds for their work have a vested interested in ‘selling poverty’ - so there’s a sort of ‘unholy alliance’ with the media in peddling negative images of places like Africa.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“However, when devising marketing campaigns, we need to be extremely careful that politicians in particular don’t grasp at the concept as a cheap way out.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">Ms Hill said the Media Development Group identified a particular gap in the print media - as opposed to radio and television, which are starting to air positive programs.&nbsp; Carol Pinot’s recent documentary Africa Open For Business, for instance was funded by the World Bank to improve the investment climate and therefore prosperity across Africa.</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“The print media is much more negative.&nbsp; In fact there’s very little being reported at all in the newspapers and magazines about Africa, as opposed to say Asia where at least there’s some coverage,” said Ms Hill.</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“As an example, the Ghanaian stock exchange regularly tops the list of the world’s highest performing stock markets, and Uganda and Kenya aren’t far behind.&nbsp; I’d have thought this is a great story for the financial press but it is hardly reported at all.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">According to Ms Hill, a recent report by the Commission for Africa found most westerners viewed Africa as one big country.</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“This ignores the diversity of circumstances in the 53 independent nations that make up the vast continent.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">The commission also found barriers to development were exaggerated by pessimistic reports. In this way negative perceptions of Africa have acted as a disincentive to investment and have in effect become reality.</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">These conclusions are confirmed by a December 2000 study by a group called the TransAfrican Forum, which found that over a three week period the New York Times and Washington Post reported 89 times on Africa.&nbsp; Even in these quality newspapers, the reports focused exclusively on AIDS, development and conflict.&nbsp; Not one of the 89 reports covered regional economic or political co-operation, or private sector activity.</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“And yet people are starting to do positive things,” said Ms Hill.&nbsp; “For instance, a couple of years ago an MBA graduate from Cameroon set up a website called Liquid Africa to help people invest in Africa online.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“Along these lines, our meeting agreed to explore the feasibility of setting up a micro investment facility for Africa, where people with 200 to 1000 pounds could invest in African ventures.&nbsp; This amount of money is in line with what people would donate to a charity in Africa.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">Other ideas proposed by the group were a directory where journalists can obtain good positive stories, and a proposal to get students of journalism and international development working together at universities.</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">“Unfortunately there’s a tension where generous people who’ve been giving to Africa for so long see that investing in Africa - and deriving a profit as a result - is somewhat mercenary.&nbsp; Many of these people have no problem investing in UK businesses and helping them grow.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">Ms Hill believes, “we need to break this perception down.&nbsp; It existed in Asia 20 to 30 years ago as well.&nbsp; But look what foreign investment has done for Asian economies since then.&nbsp; I think there’s African tigers (or lions!) out there waiting to pounce – we just need to let them.”</kw></p><br><p><kw class="krdwrd-tag-3">According to Ms Hill, “our meeting only went for 2 hours - but at least it was a start in taking stock of what has been done, and more importantly what can be done.”</kw><br></p>
  </div>
  <div class="itemFoot">
    <span class="itemAdminLink"></span> <span class="itemPermaLink"></span>
  </div>
</div></div>

